== Cette page est aussi disponible en français ==

There are many pages that start with a line like this.  On other pages that are available in multiple languages there are less intrusive links to these versions on the bottom of the page.  I prefer the second variant.  Is the former the old way of doing it and has been deprecated?  Can I freely replace the former with the latter?  A note about this should be added to HowLanguagesWork. -- JonasBernoulli

[new]
Yes, you are right. These links are the old way of doing it. Feel free to replace them. Thanks! -- AlexSchroeder

[new]
Done!  At least for French and a few English ones.  I might do some more languages another time - but this time programmatically.  Also could someone tell we what strings I have to grep for for other languages, please.  -- JonasBernoulli

[new:DrewAdams:2010-03-16 00:00 UTC]
I disagree that the new is a full replacement for the old. The new assumes that if you are reading the wiki in, say, French, then you just want to see the French version of a page. However, in some cases there are significant differences between the versions of the same page in different languages. 

I have nothing against changing to the new as a general default. But there is no reason not to allow explicit references to a different version in another language, especially if the text calling that out indicates clearly that the other-language version might not be as up-to-date as the English version. In sum, there is nothing wrong with using explicit links, if one thinks they can help users. -- DrewAdams

[new]
(Also see suggestion below.)

If think that the English page Foo should not have a link/text like "There is also a French page but it is totally not up-to-date: Fôô" that is pretty much useless to any one not speaking French and of little value to those actually speaking French.  Instead Fôô should have something like "This the French translation of: Foo. Unfortunately it is not up-to-date, so you might want to have a look at the English version also". (All this in French of course.) -- JonasBernoulli

[new:DrewAdams:2010-03-16 14:41 UTC]
I think we ''should'' not worry so much about what "''should''" be the case on individual pages. ;-)

Someone who more easily reads French might nevertheless find herself on the English page Foo (for various reasons). She might welcome the knowledge that there is also a French page Fôô, and might consult it even knowing that it might not be up to date -- for comparison on some particular point, for example. It is not unusual to be able to read a second language (e.g. English) but still feel more comfortable in one's native language.

The point is that people are different, and explicit indication helps people, themselves, decide. As I said, "I have nothing against changing to the new as a general default." It's about letting page readers (and writers) judge for themselves. Letting readers know that a version of the page in another language is not up to date helps them decide. -- DrewAdams
 
